line_number: The Legend of Good Women; Prologue F 143
context: Upon the braunches ful of blosmes° softe
I trowe° he hadde wives mo than oon;
And ech of hem had wives mo than two;
Of urine, and our bothe thinges smal°
For I shal telle ensamples mo than ten.
He knew of hem mo legendes and lives
Of Venus werkes worth his olde sho,°
And therwithal, he knew of mo proverbes
Tho bisy wrecches, ful of wo and drede!
Of Brugges were his hosen° broun
Withouten wordes mo, I wol be deed.
Among the Grekes, ful of worthinesse
Upon hir lendes,° ful of many a gore.°
And right anon, withouten wordes mo
Withouten wordes mo, they goon to bedde
He sit him up withouten wordes mo
Terme of his lif; what nedeth wordes mo?
And seide: “Sire, what nedeth wordes mo?
What ladies fairest been or best daunsinge
With othere rites mo; and atte laste
And cuppes ful of win, and milke and blood
Tel me anon withouten wordes mo
As ye han herd what nedeth wordes mo
For in the sterres, clerer than is glas,°
And deintees° mo than I can yow devise
May winne of me mo fees° thus
To have mo floures, swiche seven°
In alle thinges moor mesure
For which, withouten any wordes mo
Was in his nedes prest and corageous;
Who shal now trowe on any othes mo?
“Your lettres ful, the papir al ypleinted
“Who shal now trowe on any othes mo?
“There been mo sterres,° God wot, than a paire!”
And wente his wey withouten wordes mo.
¶Now, good men, God foryeve yow your trespas,°
His nailes whitter than the lilie flour
As seith my lord, so make us al good men;
